Ed,<br><br>
Thanks.  Your words mean more than you will ever know.  I have often wondered what will happen when I reach that place where I can climb no more.  As I get older I can see it.  It is reflected in my thoughts about that old mistress &quot;death&quot; that you and Cook reflected on in a previous post.  I have often feared there is a point where there is no reason.<br><br>
Hell, used to disarm my chute over the North because I didn't want to be a POW.  Crazy Huh!  My co-pilot felt the same, sometimes I think out of respect to me.<br><br>
Your are correct about the WORKAHOLIC, totally!  You have one other friend on this site that is also a friend of mine who struggles with that malady.  I know he has helped me to see the error.  The family suffers.  I tend to drive them the same way.  They are troopers, but at least vocal.<br><br>
I am being driven into vacation next week by necessity (not choice).  Never take it all and feel it is a weakness to ever take sick time off. 1 day in ten years.  Not good, not good at all.  I try not to drive my employees, to the point I will take on work they should do because I feel guilt about asking too much.  I can not always see the line.<br><br>
I should listen to what someone told me long ago and didn't not understand at the time.  &quot;Those who walk are runners who have found what they are seeking&quot;<br><br>
I assume it is time to practice &quot;walking without guilt&quot;<br><br>
You too are my brother with whom I trust my life, my wingman.<br><br>
Once again thanks!  (BIG WATCH, MANY DIALS, NOW TOO SMALL TO SEE) HA!<br><br>
PS.  My boss is an rotor head (same same you)  Also crazy guy.  He is almost ready to join in.
